  "A teacher records test scores for 7 students: 68, 72, 75, 78, 80, 85, 92. She wants to report a single number that best represents typical performance. Which value is the mean, and is it a reasonable summary here?": "",
  "Mean = 78.6; yes, the data are fairly symmetric with no extreme outliers": "",
  "Mean = 75; the middle score is always the mean": "",
  "Mean = 80; you just pick the most common score": "",
  "Mean = 92; the highest score is the best summary": "",
  "Mean = (68+72+75+78+80+85+92)/7 = 550/7 ≈ 78.6. With no extreme outliers and a roughly symmetric spread, the mean is a good summary.": "",
  "A real estate website lists home prices in a neighborhood: $180k, $195k, $210k, $215k, $220k, $225k, and $1.2 million. A buyer asks for the 'average' home price. Why would the median be a better measure than the mean?": "",
  "The mode should always be used for home prices": "",
  "The $1.2 million outlier pulls the mean up to about $349k, far above the typical price; the median ($215k) better represents a typical home": "",
  "The mean and median are always the same, so it doesn't matter": "",
  "The mean is always better because it uses all data": "",
  "The mean = (180+195+210+215+220+225+1200)/7 ≈ $349k, inflated by the outlier. The median ($215k) is resistant to the outlier and more representative.": "",
  "A shoe store tracks daily sales of shoe sizes: 7, 7, 8, 8, 8, 9, 9, 10, 11. The manager wants to know which size to stock the most. Which measure of central tendency should the manager use?": "",
  "The mode, because it identifies the most frequently sold size (size 8)": "",
  "The mean, because it uses all data": "",
  "The median, because it is in the middle": "",
  "The range, because it shows the spread of sizes": "",
  "The mode (size 8, appearing 3 times) tells the manager which size is in highest demand, making it the most useful measure for inventory decisions.": "",
  "A student's grades are: Homework (weight 20%) = 90, Midterm (weight 30%) = 78, Final (weight 50%) = 84. What is the student's weighted mean grade?": "",
  "83.4": "",
  "80.0": "",
  "84.0": "",
  "86.0": "",
  "Weighted mean = 0.20(90) + 0.30(78) + 0.50(84) = 18 + 23.4 + 42 = 83.4.": "",
  "A company reports that its employees' mean salary is $95,000, but the median salary is $62,000. What does this suggest about the salary distribution?": "",
